description: From Dharug guuu-wi adopted into English by white settlers in Australia from 1790.

entries.meaning: (Australia, informal, onomatopoeia) A long, loud call used to attract attention when at a distance, mainly done in the Australian bush.
(Australia, informal, with "within", also figuratively) A short distance; hailing distance.

verbs.description: cooee (third-person singular simple present cooees, present participle cooeeing, simple past and past participle cooeed)

entries.meaning: (intransitive, Australia, informal) To make such a call.
examples: ‘Look out for snakes,’ said Long Charlie, flourishing his lantern. ‘And don′t all of us be coo-eeing all the time, or when the little chap sings out we shan't be able to hear him.’
